{{Multiple image|align=right|total_width=420|image_style=border:none;|image1=PLATE8DX foruth sixth.jpg|width1=900|height1=1000|alt1=Costumes of Arab men, fourth to sixth century|image2=PLATE8CX.jpg|width2=900|height2=1000|alt2=Costumes of Arab women, fourth to sixth century.|footer=Pre-Islamic costumes of Arab men and Arab women between fourth to sixth century}}
{{Arab culture}}
'''Arab identity''' is the objective or subjective state of [[Identity (social science)|perceiving oneself]] as an Arab and as relating to being Arab. It relies on a common culture, a traditional lineage, the common land in history, shared experiences including underlying conflicts and confrontations. These commonalities are regional and [[Tribes of Arabia|tribal]]. Arab identity is defined independently of [[religious identity]], and [[Pre-Islamic Arabia|pre-dates]] the [[spread of Islam]], with historically attested [[Arab Christians|Arab Christian]] tribes and [[Jewish tribes of Arabia|Arab Jewish tribes]]. Arabs are a diverse group in terms of religious affiliations and practices. Most Arabs are [[Muslim]], with a minority adhering to other faiths, largely [[Christianity in the Middle East|Christianity]], but also [[Druze]] and [[Bahá'í Faith|Baha'i]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t7Ao8dYsCskC&lpg=PA45&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false| title=The Arabs in Palestine|accessdate=March 4, 2014|author=Ori Stendel|page=45|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=1898723249}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PmgkD3Hel5IC&lpg=PA309&pg=PA297#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Between Heaven and Hell: Islam, Salvation, and the Fate of Others|author=Mohammad Hassan Khalil|accessdate=March 1, 2014|page=297|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>

Arab identity can also be seen through a lens of local or regional identity. Throughout [[History of the Arabs|Arab history]], there have been three major national trends in the [[Arab world]]. [[Pan-Arabism]] rejects states' existing sovereignty as artificial creations and calls for full Arab unity.

==History==

{{main|History of the Arabs}}
[[File:NE 565ad-Lakhmid.jpg|thumb|widthpx|Near East in 565, showing the Ghassanids, Lakhmids, Kindah and Hejaz.]]
The Arabs are first mentioned in the mid-ninth century BCE as a people living in eastern and southern Syria, and the north of the Arabian Peninsula.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cRrGQ8bIAkC|title=The Ituraeans and the Roman Near East: Reassessing the Sources|last=Myers|first=E. A.|date=2010-02-11|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781139484817|language=en}}</ref> 
[[File:Map of expansion of Caliphate.svg|left|thumb|Expansion of the [[Caliphate]].{{legend|#a1584e|Expansion under the Prophet [[Muhammad]], 622-632}}
{{legend|#ef9070|Expansion during the [[Rashidun Caliphate]], 632-661}}
{{legend|#fad07d|Expansion during the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], 661-750}}
|220x220px]]
The Arabs appear to have been under the vassalage of the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire]] (911–605 BCE), and then the succeeding [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]] (605–539 BCE), Persian [[Achaemenid Empire]] (539–332 BCE), [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonian]]/[[Seleucid Empire]] and [[Parthian Empire]]. Arab tribes, most notably the [[Ghassanids]] and [[Lakhmids]] begin to appear in the south Syrian deserts and southern Jordan from the mid 3rd century CE onwards, during the mid to later stages of the [[Roman Empire]] and [[Sasanian Empire]].

The relation of ''{{transl|ar|ʿarab}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|ʾaʿrāb}}'' is complicated further by the notion of "lost Arabs" ''{{transl|ar|al-ʿArab al-ba'ida}}'' mentioned in the Qur'an as punished for their disbelief. All contemporary Arabs were considered as descended from two ancestors, [[Qahtanite|Qahtan]] and [[Adnan]]. During the early Muslim conquests of the 7th and 8th centuries, the Arabs forged the [[Rashidun Caliphate|Rashidun]] and then [[Umayyad Caliphate]], and later the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], whose borders touched southern [[France]] in the west, [[China]] in the east, [[Anatolia]] in the north, and the [[Sudan]] in the south. This was one of the [[List of empires|largest land empires in history]].

==Ideology==
===Arab nationalism===
{{main|Arab nationalism}}
{{See also|Nasserism|Ba'athism}}
[[File:Stevan Kragujevic, Gamal Abdel Naser u Beogradu, 1962.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] was a symbol and significant player in the rise of Arab nationalism]]
[[Arab nationalism]] is a nationalist ideology that asserts the Arabs are a nation and promotes the unity of [[Arabs|Arab people]]. In its contemporary conception, it is the belief that the Arab people are a people united by [[language]], [[culture]], [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]], [[history]], [[geography]] and interests, and that one Arab state will assemble the Arabs within its borders from the ocean to the Gulf. The Arabs believed that they were an old nation. It showed Arab pride in [[Arabic poetry]]. In the [[Islam|era of Islam]], nationalism was manifested by the feeling of the Arabs as a distinct nation within Islam. In the modern era, this idea was embodied by ideologies such as [[Nasserism]] and [[Ba'athism]], which were the most common in the Arab world, especially in the mid-twentieth century until the end of the seventies, characterized by the establishment of the [[United Arab Republic]] between [[Egypt]] and [[Syria]] and witnessed many other attempts of unity. Arab nationalism gained a new popular range as a result of the [[Arab Spring]]  and the emergence of an Arab popular trend calling for an Arab unity led by the people, not the authoritarian regimes that installed the wave of nationalism without accomplishing anything in this direction.

===Arab socialism=== 
{{main|Arab socialism}}
[[Arab socialism]] is a political [[ideology]] based on the confusion between Arab nationalism and [[socialism]]. Arab socialism differs from the socialist ideas prevalent in the Arab world.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=TORREY|first=GORDON H.|last2=DEVLIN|first2=JOHN F.|date=1965|title=Arab Socialism|jstor=24363337|journal=Journal of International Affairs|volume=19|issue=1|pages=47–62|doi=10.2307/24363337}}</ref> For many, including [[Michel Aflaq]], Arab socialism was a natural step towards the consolidation of Arab unity and freedoms, since the socialist system of ownership and development alone can overcome the remnants of [[colonialism]] in the Arab world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/no-arab-bolivars-region-implodes-arab-socialism-fizzles-out-1687981422|title=No Arab Bolivars: As region implodes, Arab socialism fizzles out|work=Middle East Eye|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cato.org/blog/coping-legacy-arab-socialism|title=Coping with the Legacy of Arab Socialism|date=2014-08-25|work=Cato Institute|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en}}</ref>

==Unity==

===Pan-Arabism=== 
{{main|Pan-Arabism}}
{{further|Arab Federation|Arab Islamic Republic|Federation of Arab Republics|Unified Political Command|United Arab Republic|United Arab States|Arab Federation}}
[[File:NasserQuwatliUAR.jpg|thumb|right|[[Egypt]]ian president Gamal Abdel Nasser signing unity pact with [[Syria]]n president [[Shukri al-Quwatli]], forming the [[United Arab Republic]], February 1958.]]
[[Pan-Arabism]] is an ideology espousing the unification of the countries of North Africa and West Asia from the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to the [[Arabian Sea]], referred to as the Arab world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1991/2/28/pan-arabism-is-not-dead-pbib-was/|title=Pan-Arabism Is Not Dead {{!}} Opinion {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref> The idea is based on the integration of some or all of the Arab countries into a single [[Politics|political]] and [[Economy|economic framework]] that removes the borders between the Arab states and establishes a strong economic, human and military state.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Pan-Arabism - Oxford Reference|url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803100303333}}</ref> Arab unity is an idea that the Arab nationalists believe as a solution to the [[backwardness]], occupation and oppression that the Arab citizen lives in all the countries of this country extending from the ocean to the Gulf.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Pan-Arabism|title=Pan-Arabism {{!}} ideology|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en}}</ref>

===Arab League===
{{main|Arab League}}
{{details|Charter of the Arab League}}
{{See also|Gulf Cooperation Council|Arab Maghreb Union}}
The [[Arab League]], formally the League of Arab States is a [[regional organization]] of [[Arab world|Arab countries]] in and around [[North Africa]], the [[Horn of Africa]] and [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabia]]. It was formed in [[Cairo]] on 22 March 1945 with six members: [[Kingdom of Egypt]], [[Kingdom of Iraq]], [[Emirate of Transjordan|Transjordan]] (renamed [[Jordan]] in 1949), [[Lebanon]], [[Saudi Arabia]], and [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Arab League|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1E1-ArabLeag/arab-league|work=The Columbia Encyclopedia|accessdate=17 December 2013|year=2013}}{{Subscription required|via=Questia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sly|first=Liz|title=Syria suspended from Arab League|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2011-11-12/world/35282109_1_arab-league-president-bashar-syrian-national-council|newspaper=Washington Post|date=12 November 2011}}</ref> Its charter provides for coordination among member states in economic matters, including trade relations, communications, cultural relations, nationalities, travel documents and permits, social relations and health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-15747941|title=Profile: Arab League|date=2017-08-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>

