==Homeland==
{{main|Arab world}}
The [[Arab world]], formally the ''Arab homeland'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Zafarul-Islam|title=The Arab World – an Arab perspective|url=http://www.milligazette.com/news/6666-the-arab-world-an-arab-perspective|website=www.milligazette.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Christopher|title=Everyday Arab Identity: The Daily Reproduction of the Arab World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C8djTtq2v5AC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Routledge|language=en|date=12 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mellor|first1=Noha|last2=Rinnawi|first2=Khalil|last3=Dajani|first3=Nabil|last4=Ayish|first4=Muhammad I.|title=Arab Media: Globalization and Emerging Media Industries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GoU-NRhn1agC&pg=PT10&lpg=PT10&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|language=en|date=20 May 2013}}</ref> also known as the ''Arab nation'' or the ''Arab states'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Majority and Minorities in the Arab World: The Lack of a Unifying Narrative|url=http://jcpa.org/article/majority-and-minorities-in-the-arab-world-the-lack-of-a-unifying-narrative/|website=Jerusalem Center For Public Affairs}}</ref> currently consists of the 22 Arab countries: [[Algeria]], [[Bahrain]], [[Comoros]], [[Djibouti]], [[Egypt]], [[Iraq]], [[Jordan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Lebanon]], [[Libya]], [[Mauritania]], [[Morocco]], [[Oman]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Qatar]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Syria]], [[Tunisia]], [[United Arab Emirates]] and [[Yemen]], occupy an area stretching from the [[Atlantic Ocean]] in the west to the [[Arabian Sea]] in the east, and from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] in the north to the [[Horn of Africa]] and the [[Indian Ocean]] in the southeast. Arab world has a combined population of around 422 million inhabitants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/unesco/events/prizes-and-celebrations/celebrations/international-days/world-arabic-language-day/ |title=World Arabic Language Day |work=UNESCO |date=18 December 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>

== Categories ==
Arab identity can be described as consisting of many interconnected parts:

=== Racial identity ===
{{main|Arabid race}}
[[File:Qahtanites.png|thumb|Traditional [[Qahtanite]] genealogy.]]
Arabs belong to the [[Semitic race|Semitic]] branch of the [[Caucasian race]], mostly [[Mediterranean race]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Leisure Hour: An Illustrated Magazine for Home Reading|date=1852|publisher=W. Stevens, Printer|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=M5NPAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA454&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=High Points in the Work of the High Schools of New York City|date=1941|publisher=Board of Education, New York City.|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=N96gAAAAMAAJ&q=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Twomey|first1=David|title=Labor and Employment Law: Text & Cases|date=2012|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=1133188281|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=eB77CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA514&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Boosahda|first1=Elizabeth|title=Arab-American Faces and Voices: The Origins of an Immigrant Community|date=2010|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292783133|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=6ZIQAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref> The Arabid race<ref>John R. Baker Race. — New York and London: Oxford University Press, 1974. — P. 625. {{ISBN|978-0-936396-04-0}}</ref> is a term for a morphological subtype of the Caucasoid race, as used in [[physical anthropology]].<ref name=TROE1>{{cite web|url=http://www.theapricity.com/snpa/chapter-XI2.htm|title=The Mediterranean race in Arabia|website=Theapricity.com|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> Some recent genetic studies have found (by analysis of the DNA of Semitic-speaking peoples), [[Y chromosome|Y-chromosomal]] links between modern Semitic-speaking peoples of the Middle East like [[Arabs]], [[Hebrews]], [[Mandaeans]], [[Samaritans]], and [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]].

Medieval Arab [[genealogist]]s divided Arabs into three groups:
* "Ancient Arabs" tribes that had vanished or been destroyed.
* "Pure Arabs" descending from Qahtan who was a descendant of Ishmael. 
* The "Arabized Arabs" descending from [[Ishmael]] the elder son of [[Abraham]].

The Arabs refuse to classify and called them as "[[white people|white]]" they identify themselves as "Arab".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zebib|first1=Laura|title=Stop Calling Me White. I Am Arab.|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/stop-calling-me-white-i-am-arab_us_58a1d4c4e4b0cd37efcfeb05|website=Huffington Post|date=13 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Beydoun|first1=Khaled A|title=Are Arabs white?|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2015/07/arabs-white-150716110921150.html|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Am I white? – the classification of Arabs in America has a messy history and it still matters|url=https://thetempest.co/2017/08/11/culture-taste/white-classification-arabs-messy-history-still-matters/|website=The Tempest|date=11 August 2017}}</ref> When it comes to Arabs it seems this important point is often lost, as see more and more attempts to position them as “white.”<ref>{{cite web|title=Comment: Why Arabs are not 'white'|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/topics/life/culture/article/2017/02/28/comment-why-arabs-are-not-white|website=Topics|language=en}}</ref>

=== Ethnic identity ===
{{main|Arabs}}
[[File:Pre Islamic Arabia.PNG|thumb|[[Arab tribes]] before the spread of Islam]]
[[Ethnic identity]] is another factor in Arab identity, who identify, linguistically, identically, culturally, societally, ancestrally, historically, politically, nationally and genealogically as "Arab".

In the modern era, it is defined who is an Arab based on these criteria:
* [[Genealogy|Genealogical]]: someone who can trace his or her ancestry to the [[Tribes of Arabia|Arab tribes]], from the [[Arabian Desert]], [[Syrian Desert]] and neighboring areas.<ref>(Regueiro et al.) 2006; found agreement by (Battaglia et al.) 2008</ref>
* [[Ancestor|Ancestral]]: belonging to Arab people, inherited from grandparents, or denoting an ancestor or ancestors.
* [[Self-concept]]: a person who defines himself as "Arab", belongs to the [[Arab Nation|Arab nation]].
* [[Personal identity|Identical]]: someone being as an Arab.
* [[Language|Linguistic]]: someone whose [[first language]], and by extension cultural expression, is [[Arabic language|Arabic]].<ref name="Jankowskip244">Jankowski, James. "Egypt and Early Arab Nationalism" in Rashid Kakhlidi, ed., Origins of Arab Nationalism, pp. 244–245</ref><ref name="Dawishp99">Quoted in Dawisha, Adeed. [https://books.google.com/books?id=PjhqEusGs0UC&pg=PA99 ''Arab Nationalism in the Twentieth Century'']. Princeton University Press. 2003, {{ISBN|0-691-12272-5}}, p. 99</ref>
* [[Culture|Cultural]]: someone who belongs to Arab culture relating to the ideas, customs, and social behavior of a society.
*[[Politics|Political]]: someone his country is a member of the League of Arab States and who is in sympathy with the aspirations of the Arab peoples. (i.e. [[Somalis]] and [[Djiboutians]]).
* [[Society|Societal]]: while self-reliance, individuality, and responsibility are taught by Arabic parents to their children, family loyalty is the greatest lesson taught in Arab families.
* [[Nationality|National]]: one who is a national of an Arab state or characteristic of [[Arab nationalism]].

=== National identity ===
{{main|Arab nationalism}}
[[File:Flag_of_Hejaz_1917.svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Flag_of_Hejaz_1917.svg|right|thumb|The [[Flag of the Arab Revolt|flag]] of the [[Arab Revolt]], its design and [[Pan-Arab colors|colors]] are the basis of many of the [[Arab states]]' [[List of Arab flags|flags]].]]
[[National identity]] is one's identity or sense of belonging to one state or to one [[nation]].<ref name=":34">{{Cite journal|url = |title = The Social Identity Theory of Inter-group Behavior.|last = Tajfel|first = H|date = 1986|journal = Psychology of Intergroup Relations|doi = |pmid = |last2 = Turner|first2 = J.C}}</ref> It is the sense of a nation as a cohesive whole, as represented by distinctive traditions, culture, language and politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url =http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/us/definition/american_english/national-identity|title =Definition of National Identity in English|date =|accessdate =|website =Oxford Dictionaries|publisher =|last =|first =|deadurl =no|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063449/http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/us/definition/american_english/national-identity|archivedate =2015-11-17|df =}}</ref> [[Arab nationalism]] is a [[Nationalism|nationalist]] [[List of political ideologies|ideology]] celebrating the glories of Arab civilization, the [[Arabic|language]] and literature of the [[Arabs]], calling for rejuvenation and [[political union]] in the [[Arab world]]. The premise of Arab nationalism is the need for an [[Ethnic group|ethnic]], [[Politics|political]], [[Culture|cultural]] and [[History|historical]] unity among the Arab peoples of the Arab countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dawisha|first=Adeed|date=2003-01-01|title=Requiem for Arab Nationalism|url=http://www.meforum.org/518/requiem-for-arab-nationalism|journal=Middle East Quarterly|language=en-US}}</ref> The main objective of Arab nationalism was to achieve the independence of Western influence of all Arab countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://martinkramer.org/sandbox/reader/archives/arab-nationalism-mistaken-identity/|title=Arab Nationalism: Mistaken Identity {{!}} Martin Kramer on the Middle East|website=martinkramer.org|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Arab political strategies with the nation in order to determine the struggle of the [[Arab world|Arab nation]] with the state system (nation-state) and the struggle of the Arab nation for unity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nzhistory.govt.nz/war/ottoman-empire/rise-of-arab-nationalism|title=Rise of Arab nationalism - The Ottoman Empire {{!}} NZHistory, New Zealand history online|website=nzhistory.govt.nz|language=en|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> The concepts of new nationalism and old nationalism are used in analysis to expose the conflict between nationalism, national ethnic nationalism, and new national political nationalism. These two aspects of national conflicts highlight the crisis known as the [[Arab Spring]], which affects the Arab world today.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ssfc0005/The%20Rise%20and%20Fall%20of%20Arab%20Nationalism.html|title=The Rise and Fall of Arab Nationalism|website=users.ox.ac.uk|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref> Suppressing the political struggle to assert the identity of the new civil state is said to clash with the original [[Ethnic group|ethnic identity]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.socialism.com/drupal-6.8/articles/short-history-arab-nationalism|title=A short history of Arab Nationalism {{!}} www.socialism.com|website=www.socialism.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>

=== Religious identity ===
{{main|Arabs#Religion}}
[[File:Allat_Palmyra_RGZM_3369.jpg|thumb|[[Allāt]] from the Ba‘alshamîn temple in Palmyra, first century AD. [[Damascus]]]]
Until about the fourth century, almost all Arabs practised polytheistic religions.<ref name="Hoyland2002">{{cite book|author=Robert G. Hoyland|title=Arabia and the Arabs: From the Bronze Age to the Coming of Islam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XaiGAgAAQBAJ|page= 139|date=11 September 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-64634-0}}</ref> Although significant [[Judaism|Jewish]] and Christian minorities developed, polytheism remained the dominant belief system in pre-Islamic, most Arabs followed a pagan religion with a number of deities, including [[Hubal]],<ref name="Hubal">{{cite web|url=http://www.islamic-awareness.org/Quran/Sources/Allah/hubal.html|title=Is Hubal The Same As Allah?|publisher=Islamic-awareness.org|accessdate=13 April 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325235432/http://www.islamic-awareness.org/Quran/Sources/Allah/hubal.html|archivedate=25 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Wadd]], [[Al-lāt|Allāt]],<ref name="autogenerated1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEcpkWjYOZQC&vq=Allat&pg=PA34|title=Dictionary of Ancient Deities|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-514504-6}}</ref> [[Manāt|Manat]], and [[Uzza]]. A few individuals, the ''[[hanif]]s'', had apparently rejected [[polytheism]] in favor of [[monotheism]] unaffiliated with any particular religion. Different theories [[Religion in pre-Islamic Arabia#Mecca|have been proposed]] regarding the role of [[Allah]] in Meccan religion.<ref name=berkey42>{{cite book|author=Jonathan Porter Berkey|title=The Formation of Islam: Religion and Society in the Near East, 600-1800|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mLV6lo4mvj0C&pg=PA42|year=2003|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-58813-3|page=42}}</ref><ref name= Robinson>{{cite book|author=Neal Robinson|title=Islam: A Concise Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2UL8AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA75|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-81773-1|page=75}}</ref><ref name= Peters>{{cite book|author=Francis E. Peters|title=Muhammad and the Origins of Islam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OrCo4VyvGkC&pg=PA110|year=1994|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-1875-8|page=110}}</ref><ref name="Peterson2007">{{cite book|author=Daniel C. Peterson|title=Muhammad, Prophet of God|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9zpbEj0xA_sC&pg=PA21|date=26 February 2007|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-0754-0|page=21}}</ref> Today the majority of Arabs are [[Muslim]]s, identities are often seen as inseparable. The "[[Verse of brotherhood]]" is the tenth [[Ayah|verse]] of the [[Quran]]ic chapter "[[Al-Hujurat]]", is about brotherhood of believers with each other.<ref>[http://abuaminaelias.com/brotherhood-in-the-quran-and-sunnah/ Brotherhood in the Quran and Sunnah | Faith in Allah الإيمان بالله<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://al-islami.com/islam/unity/brotherhood.php The Bonds of Brotherhood<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name="quranse.org">{{cite web|title=Al-Hujurat chapter|url=http://www.quranse.org/QueryEngine/index.php?Cmd=P&FromCmd=AS&b=Qur&c=49&v1=1&v2=18&DP=1&DG=1&QtID3=frchiadmi&QtID4=pickthall&BtID0=esv&BtID1=lsg&BtID2=sg21&BtID4=kjv&BL=en}}</ref> 
However, there were divergent currents in [[Pan-Arabism|Arabism]] - one [[Religion|religious]] and [[Secularity|secular]] one - throughout [[Arab history]]. After the collapse of the [[Ottoman Caliphate|Ottoman Islamic caliphate]] in the 20th century, Arab nationalism emerged on the religious front. These two trends have continued to overcome each other to this day. Now, religious fundamentalism offers an alternative to secular nationalism. There are also different religious denominations within [[Islam]] and are often valuable to religion as a whole, leading to sectarian conflict and conflict. In fact, the social and psychological distances between [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] and [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Muslims may be greater than the perceived distance between different religions. Because of this, Islam can be seen both as a unification and as a force of division in Arab identity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=García-Arenal|first=Mercedes|date=2009-01-01|title=The Religious Identity of the Arabic Language and the Affair of the Lead Books of the Sacromonte of Granada|jstor=25651684|journal=Arabica|volume=56|issue=6|pages=495–528}}</ref>

=== Cultural Identity ===
{{main|Arab culture}}
[[File:Ernst Rudolph Elegant Arab Ladies on a Terrace at Sunset.jpg|thumb|Elegant Arab Ladies on a Terrace at Sunset]]
Arab cultural identity is characterized by complete uniformity. Arab cultural space are historically so tightly interwoven.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cultural Identity in the Islamic World {{!}} MR Online|url=https://mronline.org/2009/05/17/cultural-identity-in-the-islamic-world/|website=MR Online|date=17 May 2009}}</ref> Arab cultural identity has been assessed through four measures that measure the basic characteristics of Arab culture: religiosity, grouping, belief in gender hierarchy and attitudes toward sexual behavior. The results indicate the predominance of the professional strategies that Arab social workers have learned in their training in social work, while indicating the willingness of social workers to benefit from established strategies in their culture and society, either separately or in combination with the professional.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sabry|first1=Tarik|title=Arab Cultural Studies: Mapping the Field|date=2012|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=9781848855595|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=eYq3Z3jb6XUC&dq=|language=en}}</ref> There are different aspects of Arab identity, whether ethnic, religious, national, linguistic or cultural - of different fields and analytical angles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sabry|first1=edited by Tarik|title=Arab cultural studies : mapping the field|date=2012|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=1848855591}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Anishchenkova|first1=Valerie|title=Autobiographical Identities in Contemporary Arab Culture|date=2014|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748643417|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=vByrBgAAQBAJ&dq=|language=en}}</ref>

{{Cquote|The family is still at the heart of traditional Arabic letters that the fact that the family is a basic unit of social organization in the traditional Arab contemporary society may explain why it continues to exercise a significant influence on the formation of identity. At the heart of social and economic activities, this institution is still very coherent. Exercise the early and most lasting influence on the person's affiliations.—[[Halim Barakat]]}}

=== Linguistic identity ===
{{main|Arabic}}
[[File:Epitaph Imru-l-Qays Louvre AO4083.jpg|thumb|Arabic epitaph of [[Imru' al-Qais]], son of 'Amr, king of all the Arabs", inscribed in [[Nabataean script]]. Basalt, dated in 7 Kislul, 223, viz. December 7, 328 AD. Found at [[Namara inscription|Nemara]] in the [[Hauran]] ([[Southern Syria]]).]]
For some Arabs, beyond [[language]], [[race (human categorization)|race]], religion, [[tribe]] or region. Arabic; hence, can be considered as a common factor among all Arabs. Since the [[Arabic|Arabic language]] also exceeds the country's border, the Arabic language helps to create a sense of [[Arab nationalism]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.britac.ac.uk/arab-origins-identity-history-and-islam/|title=Arab Origins: Identity, History and Islam - British Academy Blog|date=2015-07-20|work=British Academy Blog|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref> According to the Iraqi world exclusive Cece, "it must be people who speak one language one heart and one soul, so should form one [[nation]] and thus one [[country]]." There are two sides to the coin, argumentative. While the Arabic language as one language can be a unifying factor, the language is often not unique at all. Accents vary from region to region, there are wide differences between written and spoken versions, many countries host bilingual citizens, many Arabs are illiterate. This leads us to examine other identifying aspects of Arabic identity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/841752039|title=Everyday Arab identity : the daily reproduction of the Arab world|last=D.|first=Phillips, Christopher, Ph.|date=2013-01-01|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415684880|oclc=841752039}}</ref> [[Arabic]], a Semitic language from the [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic language family]]. [[Modern Standard Arabic]] serves as the [[Standard language|standardized]] and [[literary language|literary]] variety of Arabic used in writing, as well as in most formal speech, although it is not used in daily speech by the overwhelming majority of Arabs. Most Arabs who are functional in [[Modern Standard Arabic]] acquire it through education and use it solely for writing and formal settings.

=== Political identity ===
{{main|Politics of the Arab League}}
[[File:Transportation.PNG|thumb|220x220px|A map of the Arab world.]]
Arab political identity characterized by restraint, tolerance, compassion, hospitality, generosity, tolerance restraint, proper conduct, equality and unanimity. Arab countries to redefine politics are linked to the fact that the political culture behind the Arabs has been overrun for centuries by successive political.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabs at the Crossroads: Political Identity and Nationalism {{!}} Middle East Policy Council|url=http://www.mepc.org/arabs-crossroads-political-identity-and-nationalism|website=www.mepc.org|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hoyt|first1=Paul D.|title=Legitimacy, Identity, and Political Development in the Arab World|jstor=254461|journal=Mershon International Studies Review|pages=173–176|doi=10.2307/254461|date=1998}}</ref> The vast majority of the citizens of the Arab countries view themselves and are seen by outsiders as "Arabs". Their sense of the Arab nation is based on their common denominators: language, culture, ethnicity, social and political experiences, economic interests and the collective memory of their place and role in history.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Eid|first1=Paul|title=Being Arab: Ethnic and Religious Identity Building among Second Generation Youth in Montreal|date=2007|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|isbn=9780773577350|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=aalO4QlgAgYC&dq=|language=en}}</ref>

The relative importance of these factors is estimated differently by different groups and frequently disputed. Some combine aspects of each definition, as done by Palestinian [[Habib Hassan Touma]]:<ref name="Toumapxviii">1996, p.xviii</ref> 
{{Cquote|"One who is a national of an Arab state, has command of the Arabic language, and possesses a fundamental knowledge of Arab tradition, that is, of the manners, customs, and political and social systems of the culture.}}
The [[Arab League]], a regional organization of [[countries]] intended to encompass the Arab world, defines an Arab as:
{{Cquote|An Arab is a person whose language is Arabic, who lives in an Arab country, and who is in sympathy with the aspirations of the Arab peoples.<ref>Dwight Fletcher Reynolds, ''Arab folklore'': a handbook, (Greenwood Press: 2007), p.1.</ref>}}

