{{Infobox person | name = Kurt Wise | residence = [[Cleveland, Georgia]] | image = | image_size = 156px | caption = | birth_name = Kurt Patrick Wise | birth_date = 1959 | birth_place = United States | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | known = Advocate of [[young earth creationism]] | occupation = Director of [[Truett McConnell University]]'s Creation Research Center | title = | salary = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | spouse = Marie B. Wise | partner = | children = Katrina Joy (Wise)Smith and Esther Lynn (Wise) Goforth and 4 grandchildren
| relations = | website = | footnotes = | employer = | height = | weight = }}
'''Kurt Patrick Wise''' (born 1959) is an American [[young Earth creationism|young earth creationist]] who serves as the Director of Creation Research Center at [[Truett McConnell University]]. He has a PhD in [[paleontology]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/magazine/25wwln-geologists-t.html?mcubz=1| title=Rock of Ages, Ages of Rock |publisher=[[New York Times Magazine]] | year=1998 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2017-08-30}}</ref> He writes in support of creationism and works for the [[Creation Museum]].
==Biography== In 1989, Wise earned a Ph.D. in [[paleontology]] from [[Harvard University]]. In addition, he has an M.A. in [[geology]] from Harvard University and a B.A. Geology from the [[University of Chicago]]. In 1998, [[Robert Schadewald]] described Wise as influential on "modern creationism as it is practiced at its higher levels."<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/rncse/18/3/1998-international-conference-creationism | title=The 1998 International Conference on Creationism |publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] | year=1998 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref>
Starting in fall 2009 he has been the director of [[Truett McConnell University]]'s newly created Creation Research Center in [[Cleveland, Georgia]].<ref name="Truett-McConnellAnnouncement">{{cite news | url=http://www.truett.edu/article-list/428-creation-research-center-established-at-tmc.html | title=Creation Research Center has been established | publisher=[[Truett-McConnell College]] | year=2009 | first= | last= | accessdate=2014-04-09 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145602/http://www.truett.edu/article-list/428-creation-research-center-established-at-tmc.html | archivedate=2014-04-13 | df= }}</ref> Between August 2006 and May 2009 he taught at [[Southern Baptist Theological Seminary]] as director of the school's Center for Theology and Science, a job in which he was preceded by [[intelligent design]] advocate [[William Dembski]].<ref name=sbts>{{cite news | url=http://www.sbts.edu/academics/Faculty/Theology/Kurt_Wise.aspx | title=Kurt P. Wise | publisher=[[Southern Baptist Theological Seminary]] (Archived) | year=2008 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2009-08-18 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071222161853/http://www.sbts.edu/academics/Faculty/Theology/Kurt_Wise.aspx |archivedate = 2007-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2006/aprilweb-only/117-22.0.html | title=The Other ID Opponents | publisher=[[Christianity Today]] | date=April 2006 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2008-08-18}}</ref> He had previously taught at [[Bryan College]] in [[Dayton, Tennessee]] where he served as Director of the Center for Origins Research and as an Associate Professor of Science<ref name=sbts/> for seventeen years.<ref name="Truett-McConnellAnnouncement"/>
He served as consultant to the [[Answers in Genesis]] [[Creation Museum]] which opened in 2007.<ref name=heaton>{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/rncse/27/1-2/visit-to-new-creation-museum | title=A Visit to the New Creation 'Museum' |publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] | year=2007 | first=Timothy | last=Heaton | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref> [[Timothy H. Heaton]], another scientist who studied under [[Stephen Jay Gould]], knows Wise as "a less propaganda-oriented creationist" than [[Ken Ham]], the leader of Answers in Genesis, and said that Wise's influence on the displays was apparent.<ref name=heaton/>
==Views and criticism== Wise has said he believes, according to a [[Biblical literalism|literal reading of the Bible]], "that the earth is young, and the universe is young, I would suggest that it's less than ten thousand years in age." He believes that science can be used to support and demonstrate these claims.<ref name=telling>"[http://www.abc.net.au/science/kelvin/files/s194.htm 'Telling Lies for God'? One Man's Crusade]". ''Quantum''. July 17, 1997.</ref> Despite believing that science supports his position, Wise has written that: {{quote|Although there are scientific reasons for accepting a young earth, I am a young age creationist because that is my understanding of the Scripture. As I shared with my professors years ago when I was in college, if all the evidence in the universe turns against creationism, I would be the first to admit it, but I would still be a creationist because that is what the Word of God seems to indicate.<ref name=six>Kurt Wise. [http://creationontheweb.com/content/view/4044/ ''In Six Days: Why 50 Scientists Choose to Believe in Creation'']. John Ashton, Ed. Accessed May 17, 2008.</ref>}} As a young child interested in science, Wise tentatively adopted an [[old Earth creationism|old Earth creationist]] point of view after doing a science fair project on the [[geologic column]], but was not completely satisfied with that decision:
{{quote|What nagged me was that even if the days were long periods of time, the order was still out of whack. After all, science said the sun came before the earth—or at least at the same time—and the Bible said that the earth came three days before the sun. Whereas science said that the sea creatures came before plants and the land creatures came before flying creatures, the Bible indicated that plants preceded sea creatures and flying creatures preceded land creatures. On the other hand, making the days millions of years long seemed to take away most of the conflict. I thus determined to shelve these problems in the back recesses of my mind. It didn't work. Over the next couple of years, the conflict of order nagged me.<ref name=six/>}}
Later, as a sophomore in high school, he took a newly purchased Bible and a pair of scissors and cut out every verse which could not be interpreted literally if scientific determinations on the [[age of the earth]] and [[evolution]] were true. He pursued this task with a flashlight under the covers of his bed for several months; at the end, he had removed so much material that "with the cover of the Bible taken off, I attempted to physically lift the Bible from the bed between two fingers. Yet, try as I might, and even with the benefit of intact margins throughout the pages of Scripture, I found it impossible to pick up the Bible without it being rent in two."<ref name="six"/> Wise decided to reject evolution instead of Biblical literalism, deciding:
{{quote|...that the rejection of evolution does not necessarily involve the rejection of all of science. In fact, I have come to learn that science owes its very existence and rationale to the claims of Scripture. On the other hand, I have also learned that evolution is not the only claim of modern science which must be rejected if Scripture is assumed to be true.<ref name=six/>}}
Biologist and popular [[atheism|atheist]] author [[Richard Dawkins]] called Wise a truly honest creationist because he is willing to accept creationism even if he admitted "all the evidence in the universe" was against it.<ref name="Dawkins">{{cite news | url=https://scepsis.net/eng/articles/id_2.php | title=Sadly, an Honest Creationist | publisher=[[Scepsis]] | year=2001 | first=Richard | last=Dawkins | accessdate=2015-11-30}}</ref> Dawkins, referring to Wise's testimony, criticized what he perceived as [[intellectual dishonesty]]:
{{quote|Kurt Wise doesn't need the challenge; he volunteers that, even if all the evidence in the universe flatly contradicted Scripture, and even if he had reached the point of admitting this to himself, he would still take his stand on Scripture and deny the evidence. This leaves me, as a scientist, speechless... We have it on the authority of a man who may well be creationism's most highly qualified and most intelligent scientist that no evidence, no matter how overwhelming, no matter how all-embracing, no matter how devastatingly convincing, can ever make any difference.<ref name="Dawkins"/>}}
==Books== * Kurt Wise, ''Faith, Form, and Time: What the Bible Teaches and Science Confirms About Creation and the Age of the Universe''. B&H Publishing Group, 2002. {{ISBN|0-8054-2462-8}} * Kurt Wise and Sheila A. Richardson, ''Something from Nothing: Understanding What You Believe About Creation and Why''. (B&H Publishing Group, January 2004) {{ISBN|0-8054-2779-1}}
